body:
The current parser always creates a mocked zero-argument `sample()` method for covergroups, even when the covergroup is declared `with function sample(<formals>)`.  As a result, calls like `g1.sample(x)` triggered: `Too many arguments in function call to FUNC 'sample'`. An example might be:

```
module t;
    covergroup cg(int x) with function sample(int addr, bit is_read);
    endgroup

    cg cov1 = new(42);

    function void run();
        cov1.sample(16, 1'b1);
    endfunction
```

Fix in this PR parses and attaches the declared formal parameter list to the covergroup’s sample method, and adds dedicated tests. 

Additionally, because the current grammar allows illegal forms (e.g., `covergroup extends (tf_port_list) coverage_eventE`), this PR realigns the grammar with IEEE, eliminating this issue. The semantic actions are currently duplicated across the two `covergroup_declaration` alternatives. This is temporary - once proper `covergroup extends` handling lands, the duplication will go away, so extracting a helper now isn’t worthwhile.
